
Here are the enhanced Constitution-style sections for the Ethics
Oversight Council, Transitional Voting Mechanisms, and
Enforcement Clauses, fully aligned with the no-single-leader
principle inspired by Arthur King’s Round Table.

Article XI – Global Ethics Oversight Council (“Ethics Round
Table”)Section 1. Composition & Tenure

Comprised of twelve independent members, each serving staggered
four‑year terms (max one reappointment), ensuring continuity
and renewal.

Members represent diverse domains: indigenous ethics,
technology, environmental justice, public health, wisdom
traditions, law, social equity.

Selection: half nominated by regional federations, half by civil
society and academic bodies; no member may hold governmental or
corporate office to preserve independence (medium.com).

Section 2. Leadership Without a Leader

Deliberations guided by rotating facilitators, with no permanent
chair, echoing the Round Table: all members sit equally, no
head-of-table.

Decisions arise through consensus-seeking deliberation, and
where consensus fails, super-majority (≥ 9/12) votes.

Section 3. Mandate & Powers

Reviews all proposals concerning emerging global technologies,
AI, biotech, surveillance, geoengineering, climate
interventions.

Issues binding ethical opinions that inform Global Assembly and
Global Council decisions; if advice is overruled, a public
justification must be published.

Hosts public ethics forums, enabling global citizen engagement
and transparency, in the spirit of pluralistic dialogue
(en.wikipedia.org).

Section 4. Accountability & Transparency

Publishes annual ethical impact reports.

Citizens globally may petition for review—if ≥1 million global
signatures are collected, the Council must convene an ad hoc
review panel.

Article XII – Transition & Voting Mechanisms (“Founding
Convening & Citizen Participation”)Section 1. Founding
Convening (Global Constitutional Convention)

A Founding Assembly of 500 delegates: 60% nationally elected,
20% civil society/citizen‑jury appointed, 20% reserved for
Indigenous Peoples and historically marginalized communities.

All elections and selections conducted with universal voter
registration, online and in-person, with verifiable digital and
paper ballots.

Section 2. Voting Principles

All votes use secret, verifiable ballots.

Weighted principle: each vote equal, regardless of region or
population.

Global referenda require a turnout threshold (≥ 60%) and
≥ two-thirds approval to pass foundational amendments.

Section 3. Citizen Juries & Deliberative Panels

For major global decisions (e.g. amendments, resource usage
thresholds, ethical override), randomly selected citizen juries
of 100–200 people convene for open deliberation.

Their recommendations are published alongside Assembly debates,
providing civic guidance and legitimacy.

Article XIII – Enforcement & Compliance MechanismsSection 1.
Global Court of Humanity & Nature

Judges appointed in panels of nine, serving five-year
overlapping terms, selected by Ethics Round Table and Regional
Federations jointly.

Has jurisdiction over:

Crimes against humanity, genocide, ecocide

Violations of individual or environmental rights under this
Constitution

Refusal to implement binding ethical opinions, unless publicly
justified

Section 2. Enforcement Service

A Transnational Compliance Service of peacekeepers,
environmental inspectors, legal monitors, selected on merit,
diverse background, and functional rotation.

Assigned to regions refusing compliance, investigations require
Court authorization.

Section 3. Escalation Protocol

A violation is reported by citizens, NGOs, or the Global
Council.

Ethics Round Table conducts preliminary ethical review; if
binding advice unheeded → Court intervenes.

Court can issue orders: sanctions, economic restrictions,
compliance timelines.

If a sovereign refuses Court order, the Global Council may
impose proportionate diplomatic measures, supported by Civil
Service logistics.

Section 4. No King, No Veto

There is no single executive or veto-player—all enforcement
operates via collective bodies, bound by consensus rules.

Even the Global Council acts by rotating presidencies, each
region leading limited mandates with oversight.

